  <brief_title>Efficacy of Opioid-free Anesthesia in Reducing Postoperative Pain in Chronic Pain Patients Undergoing Spinal Surgery</brief_title>
  <official_title>Efficacy of Opioid-free Anesthesia in Reducing Postoperative Pain in Chronic Pain Patients Undergoing Spinal Surgery: A Pilot Study</official_title>
  <sponsors>
    <lead_sponsor>
      <agency>Ben Lim</agency>
      <agency_class>Other</agency_class>
    </lead_sponsor>
  </sponsors>
  <source>University of Saskatchewan</source>
  <oversight_info>
    <has_dmc>No</has_dmc>
  </oversight_info>
  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      The objective of this trial is to determine whether an opioid-free general anesthetic (OFA)
      technique utilizing ketamine, dexmedetomidine, and lidocaine infusions can help reduce
      postoperative pain in opiate-dependent chronic pain patients (CPPs) undergoing spine surgery
      when compared with traditional opioid-containing techniques. It is expected that this OFA
      regimen will have a measurable reduction on postoperative opioid consumption and pain scores
      in CPPs.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
